{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":82419,"duration_api_ms":53549,"num_turns":6,"result":"All checks pass: 683 integration + 341 lib tests, clippy clean, fmt clean.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"change_summary\": \"Twentieth remediation round addressing 1 amendment: Made fail_run's snapshot write at engine.rs:5133 best-effort instead of propagating via bare `?`. Previously, if the pre-backoff recovery path called fail_run and fail_run's own snapshot write also failed (persistent disk I/O error), the `?` propagated the error without emitting the run_failed journal event (lines 5146-5151), leaving the journal with a stage_failed event but no run_failed event and the on-disk snapshot in its stale state. Now the snapshot write is wrapped in `if let Err` with `eprintln!` logging, and execution always proceeds to emit the run_failed journal event. The journal is authoritative for derive_resume_state, so recording the run failure there is more valuable than a consistent snapshot when the disk is degraded. This makes fail_run fully best-effort for persistence: both the snapshot write and the journal event emission (already best-effort via `if let Ok` and `let _`) are wrapped in error-logging paths, and the function always returns Err with the original stage failure.\",\n  \"outstanding_risks\": [\n    \"Process group kill cannot be implemented due to #![forbid(unsafe_code)] — pre_exec(setsid) requires unsafe, and std::process::Command::process_group is nightly-only. Grandchildren spawned by claude/codex CLI may survive as orphans after the parent is killed on timeout/cancel.\",\n    \"If both the snapshot write AND the journal append fail in fail_run (truly broken filesystem), the run_failed event is lost entirely. The function still returns Err, so the caller sees the failure, but on-disk state has neither an updated snapshot nor a journal event. This is acceptable — if the filesystem is completely broken, no code path can produce valid on-disk state, and the operator must intervene manually.\",\n    \"The eprintln! in fail_run's snapshot error path goes to stderr rather than a structured log. This is consistent with the rest of the engine codebase which uses eprintln! for diagnostic output (see lease_service.rs, daemon_loop.rs). A future migration to tracing::warn! would provide structured logging but is outside the scope of this retry hardening task.\",\n    \"The BinaryNotFound failure class name is used for both missing binaries and missing API keys. Doc comments clarify this dual use as a general 'fatal infrastructure prerequisite' signal.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"description\": \"Changed fail_run's snapshot write at engine.rs:5133 from bare `?` propagation to best-effort `if let Err` with `eprintln!` logging. The function now always proceeds to emit the run_failed journal event (lines 5146-5151) regardless of whether the snapshot write succeeds. Added a detailed comment explaining the rationale: the journal is authoritative for derive_resume_state, so recording the failure there is more valuable than a consistent snapshot when the disk is degraded.\",\n      \"order\": 1,\n      \"status\": \"completed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"description\": \"Verified existing test snapshot_write_failure_during_backoff_routes_through_fail_run (from CR19) still passes: BackoffFailingSnapshotWriteStore triggers a disk error on the pre-backoff snapshot write, the engine catches the error and routes through fail_run_result, and fail_run's own snapshot write succeeds (because the summary no longer starts with 'retrying'). The test asserts: (a) engine returns error, (b) on-disk snapshot is in Failed state, (c) stage_failed journal event present with will_retry=true, (d) run_failed journal event present.\",\n      \"order\": 2,\n      \"status\": \"completed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"description\": \"Ran cargo fmt to fix a minor formatting difference where rustfmt preferred the if-let binding on a single line instead of the multi-line form.\",\n      \"order\": 3,\n      \"status\": \"completed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"description\": \"Verified all 683 integration tests pass, 341 lib tests pass, cargo clippy clean, cargo fmt --check clean.\",\n      \"order\": 4,\n      \"status\": \"completed\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"validation_evidence\": [\n    \"cargo test: 683 integration tests passed, 0 failed, 0 ignored\",\n    \"cargo test --lib: 341 lib tests passed, 0 failed, 0 ignored\",\n    \"cargo clippy: no warnings or errors (Checking ralph-burning → Finished dev profile)\",\n    \"cargo fmt --check: no formatting differences (exit 0, no output)\",\n    \"fail_run at engine.rs:5133-5144 now uses if-let-Err with eprintln! for best-effort snapshot write, ensuring the run_failed journal event at lines 5146-5151 is always emitted regardless of snapshot write outcome\",\n    \"The journal event emission itself is already best-effort (line 5149: if let Ok, line 5150: let _), so fail_run now has a fully best-effort persistence strategy: both snapshot and journal operations log errors but never prevent the Err return\",\n    \"snapshot_write_failure_during_backoff_routes_through_fail_run test passes: confirms the pre-backoff → fail_run_result → fail_run path works correctly, with the run ending in Failed state and both stage_failed and run_failed journal events present\",\n    \"All 4 resume_state_tests unit tests pass: terminal_failure_clears_retry_tracking, resume_after_retryable_failure_preserves_attempt, resume_without_prior_failures_starts_at_attempt_1, completion_round_advance_resets_retry_tracking\",\n    \"All 5 classify_exit_tests unit tests pass: exit_127_returns_binary_not_found, exit_1_returns_transport_failure, exit_0_returns_transport_failure, signal_killed_returns_transport_failure, signal_6_returns_transport_failure\"\n  ]\n}\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"2ab56341-dc03-426c-ace5-dda05f3b0827","total_cost_usd":0.63960825,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_crea